Narrative:
At 2:23pm:  WeRide driverless vehicle (vehicle 1) with a safety operator seated in front passenger seat, was travelling 45mph without much traffic ahead when a BMW x3 (vehicle 2) travelling in the adjacent left lane and in the same direction, merged into vehicle 1's left front quarter panel. Vehicle 1 and Vehicle 2 sustained moderate damages.
After discussing the incident with vehicle 2's driver, they admitted they were attempting to make an upcoming right turn off the expressway. They initiated 2 consecutive right lane changes abruptly before hitting vehicle 1 on their last attempted lane change.
After the initial impact, vehicle 1 was forced out of the initial lane, onto a divide, and ultimately came to a stop on the shoulder of the expressway. At this time both occupants of vehicle 1 and vehicle 2 were able to assess respective damages and exchange information. It was determined that there were no injuries. WeRide Vehicle (Vehicle 1) required a tow back to the facility.

On April [XXX], 2025 at 8:31 AM a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped at the curb facing north on [XXX] for a passenger drop-off when an SUV traveling northbound on [XXX] passed the Waymo AV. As the SUV passed the stationary Waymo AV, the passenger side of the SUV made contact with the rear driver side of the Waymo AV. A passenger, who was seated in the rear of the Waymo AV, was not belted at the time of the collision, likely because they were preparing to exit the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was in the right lane, traveling east on [XXX] in Las Vegas. An SUV (Vehicle 2) to the left of the Zoox vehicle, was traveling ahead in the same direction in the adjacent lane. Just as the Zoox vehicle entered the intersection, the SUV suddenly veered right across the path of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked hard in response to the encroaching SUV, the Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy, and shortly after, the front passenger side of the SUV made contact with the front driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV rotated counterclockwise after impact and the rear passenger side of the SUV made contact with the rear driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV sustained major damage with airbag deployment and the Zoox vehicle sustained moderate damage to the driver side. Both vehicles were towed from the scene. The police and EMS arrived at the scene. The Zoox vehicle operator reported "body soreness" and "limping" a few hours after the collision.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 8:28 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving two SUV's, a passenger car, and a pick up truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in autonomous mode facing south at a red light as the lead vehicle in the second from the right lane when an SUV traveling northbound in an oncoming traffic lane ran the red light.  As the oncoming SUV entered the intersection, it made contact with a passenger car traveling east on [XXX].  The oncoming SUV continued through the intersection and swerved to narrowly miss a pedestrian before making contact with the front of the Waymo AV and the front driver side of a stationary pickup truck to the right of the Waymo AV.  The impact from the oncoming SUV caused the Waymo AV to contact another SUV that was also stationary to the left of the Wayo AV at the red traffic light.  The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the oncoming SUV made contact.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  The Waymo AV sustained damage to the front and rear of the vehicle, necessitating a tow from the scene.  The oncoming SUV sustained damage to the front and driver side.  The stationary SUV that was contacted sustained damage to the passenger side.  The Waymo test driver was transported to a local hospital for medical treatment.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 1 of Standing General order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment, a vehicle involved was towed away, and because of airbag deployment.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of NHTSA Report ID: 30270-9476-2.

On JUL-2024, Volkswagen Group of America, Inc. ("VW") filed an Incident Report (NHTSA-provided Report ID-1420-7995 - the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "SGO"). The subject vehicle referred to in the Report contains the Reporter's  software and hardware. Since the Reporter is also a Reporting Entity under the SGO, the Reporter hereby submits this report. In order to avoid duplications and additional CBI requests, this submission includes the publicly available information of the Report and incorporates the Report by reference. This submission is based on the information provided to the Reporter by VW. The Reporter currently believes that it has no independent knowledge of the information in this report.
From Volkswagen:
The subject vehicle (autonomous vehicle - AV) was stopped at a red traffic light, in a queue of vehicles, heading west on [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], with autonomous driving (AD) mode engaged. Once the light turned green, the queue of vehicles started to move forward, the AV started to move forward with the queue, and prior to crossing the intersection, the AV was struck from behind by an SUV. After impact the safety driver of the AV applied the brakes to disengage AD mode and then proceeded to find a safe spot to assess the incident by turning right onto [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. The driver of the SUV followed the AV to a safe location to assess the incident and exchange contact information. There were no reported injuries, airbag deployments, or tow-aways between either party involved.  The AV sustained minor damage to the rear of the vehicle including the rear bumper cover, rear bumper carrier, and a rear facing camera. The SUV damage was reported as scratches and dents to the front bumper cover. Both vehicles were able to safely drive away from the scene. VWGoA does not plan to investigate the incident any further as the facts and circumstances do not indicate any issue with the vehicle's performance.

The May vehicle is approaching a lane change. It signals the lane change appropriately early and begins to gradually decelerate for the change. The trailing SUV continues to accelerate while the May vehicle is simultaneously decelerating, and eventually changes lanes directly into the May vehicle. Trailing SUV drives away without slowing meaningfully, disappearing around an upcoming turn. May vehicle deceleration never exceeds -1.3m/s2, so there is no plausible reason a responsible driver would not have had adequate time to adjust their speed or path to avoid a collision.

The May vehicle was in autonomous mode on experimental test software (not deployed to the Commercial fleet), in light snow conditions.  A vehicle behind the AV was traveling approximately the same speed as the May shuttle. The May AV began to slow for an object ahead. Due to weather conditions, the AV misclassified a speed limit sign as a pedestrian, which intersected with the predicted trajectory of the AV. This caused the May AV to apply additional braking to avoid the projected collision with the misclassified object. The following vehicle did not react promptly when the May AV started to slow down, resulting in the following vehicle braking too late to avoid collision and impacting the May AV from behind.  The following vehicle then pulled around the May vehicle and drove away.  Resimulation of this event with an upcoming software version shows that the May AV would not misidentify the non-exist object so would not have decelerated unnecessarily. This improved software is set to be deployed to the full commercial fleet soon. In addition, per May policy, the commercial fleet would not operate in weather conditions like those present in this incident.

The subject vehicle was driving in the far right lane with the flow of traffic at approximately 30km/h (18mph). As the subject vehicle passed in front of the Honda Pilot, the Honda Pilot began to exit the parking lot without yielding. The Honda Pilot's front bumper collided with the right rear part of the subject vehicle, causing damage to the right rear body and rear right wheel of the subject vehicle. The damage to the right rear wheel of the subject vehicle required tow truck assistance.  The Honda Pilot sustained damage to its front bumper but did not require tow truck assistance.  No persons have reported injuries.  No other vehicles or other property were involved in the incident.  On the scene of the incident, the driver of the Honda Pilot admitted fault for the accident to the subject vehicle's operators.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in stop and go traffic on the [XXX] in Gardena, California with the L3 ADS activated. The test route selected by the driver in the vehicle's navigation system indicated an upcoming exit, so the driver began to prepare for a lane change towards the highway exit by deactivating the L3 ADS and activating the turn signal. Once the vehicle was in conventional driving mode, the driver looked for a gap in the adjacent lane to merge towards the exit lane, applied the brakes, and slowed the vehicle down. The SUV following the Mercedes-Benz vehicle did not respond in time to the vehicle's braking and contacted the rear of the Mercedes-Benz approximately 10 seconds after the L3 ADS was deactivated.  The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were driven from the scene of the incident.

On Feb [XXX], 2023, at 10:15am CST a Kodiak Robotics autonomous Kenworth Class 8 semi-truck (Kodiak AV) traveling northbound on [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] in [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], Texas was rear-ended by a crossover SUV. The Kodiak AV was traveling in the right lane of a three-lane portion of [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. While driving down the highway, a crossover SUV traveling in the left lane abruptly swerved out of its lane, across the center lane, and into the right lane where it collided with the rear left corner of the trailer attached to the Kodiak AV. Summary of incidentLeading up to the event, the autonomy system functioned as expected, following the route through the intersection, slowing appropriately for other road users and the red light.  Vehicle autonomous behavior was performing as expected and did not require a takeover.Description of event:16:17:30 May vehicle, traveling East on [XXX], in full working order with no errors, autonomously navigates the [XXX] and [XXX] intersection.16:17:35 May vehicle autonomously begins to slow to match the speed of a vehicle several car lengths ahead merging into our lane from the right.16:17:37 By means of an accelerator pedal push the vehicle is moved into manual mode by the safety operator - from this point forward, the vehicle remains under control of the safety operator.16:17:43 Manual acceleration command via the pedal increases.16:17:44 Safety operator manually continues straight which, due to the slight change in angle of the road, brings the May vehicle into contact with the first vehicle to the right.16:17:44 Safety operator manually applies brake.16:17:45 With the manual brake command now at maximum the May vehicle makes contact with the second vehicle.Vehicle indicators for manual or autonomy mode:The visual indicator for autonomy was functioning properly and as expected in the time leading up to and during the event.The audio communication device in the vehicle was functioning properly and was used to call for assistance and to report the incident.The audio beep to indicate a state change was functioning properly.The safety operator had some audio indication that he had exited autonomy and entered manual operation, and he had full visual indication on his dashboard.

- The subject vehicle of this report was procured by and up-fitted to ADS L4 by May Mobility with a May Mobility automated driving kit.
- The content of this report, including the summary of incident below, is the information as Toyota received from May Mobility on Aug [XXX], 2021.
Summary of incident (as Toyota received from May Mobility):
Leading up to the event, the autonomy system functioned as expected, following the route through the intersection, slowing appropriately for other road users and the red light. Vehicle autonomous behavior was performing as expected and did not require a takeover.
Description of event:
16:17:30 May vehicle, traveling East on [XXX], in full working order with no errors, autonomously navigates the [XXX] and [XXX] intersection.
16:17:35 May vehicle autonomously begins to slow to match the speed of a vehicle several car lengths ahead merging into our lane from the right.
16:17:37 By means of an accelerator pedal push the vehicle is moved into manual mode by the safety operator - from this point forward, the vehicle remains under control of the safety operator.
16:17:43 Manual acceleration command via the pedal increases.
16:17:44 Safety operator manually continues straight which, due to the slight change in angle of the road, brings the May vehicle into contact with the first vehicle to the right.
16:17:44 Safety operator manually applies brake.
16:17:45 With the manual brake command now at maximum the May vehicle makes contact with the second vehicle.
Vehicle indicators for manual or autonomy mode:
The visual indicator for autonomy was functioning properly and as expected in the time leading up to and during the event.
The audio communication device in the vehicle was functioning properly and was used to call for assistance and to report the incident.
The audio beep to indicate a state change was functioning properly.
The safety operator had some audio indication that he had exited autonomy and entered manual operation, and he had full visual indication on his dashboard.

At about 11:35 am our vehicle (car 1) was waiting behind a USPS truck to make an unprotected left turn, meanwhile one other vehicle (car 2) waited behind our vehicle.   Another non involved vehicle notices the queue of vehicles and passes on the right in the bike lane.  As the USPS truck begins to make the turn, car 1 begins to move forward at 7 MPH then slowed to 3 MPH when yielding to the vehicle passing in the bike lane. Car 2 directly behind us strikes our passenger rear bumper.  The safety driver then disengaged the vehicle (car 1) and moved into a nearby parking lot to exchange information.
